  <h2>Bel Aire Is a Growing Suburb With Older Core Neighborhoods</h2>
  <p>The older parts of Bel Aire — homes built in the 70s and 80s — are starting to show their age. Systems are at or past end-of-life, kitchens and bathrooms need updating, and some properties have deferred maintenance that's accumulated for years. These are the homes we buy most often in Bel Aire.</p>
  <p>The newer construction on the city's edges is a different story — higher price points, buyers who can finance conventionally, less need for a cash buyer. But for the older inventory, we're often the most practical option for sellers who don't want a renovation project.</p>
